{"ts":"2026-06-27T19:14:59.108Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"ebwkozpn","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_4_LOGIN_ADMIN_CLIENT_PORTAL.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 4 Secure Login, Client Portal & Admin Oversight Console\n  2 | \n  3 | This document establishes the strategic, enterprise-grade architecture, implementation details, and future backend contracts for **Phase 4** of the GFF AI Platform. \n  4 | \n  5 | In Phase 4, GFF AI delivers an advanced, premium, **high-fidelity presentation interface** representing the ultimate Sovereign Operating System for enterprise AI governance. This frontend is carefully designed with a zero-trust, decoupled aesthetic, ensuring that client-facing boards and internal GFF administrators can configure, simulate, and audit multi-agent system states with total security and confidence.\n  6 | \n  7 | ---\n  8 | \n  9 | ## 1. Executive Narrative & Visual Metaphor\n 10 | \n 11 | ### 1.1. The \"Air-Gapped Cockpit\"\n 12 | To provide boards of directors and enterprise security teams with absolute risk containment, the GFF AI Portal operates on an architecture metaphor of the **Air-Gapped Cockpit**. Just as a sophisticated flight simulator provides full-fidelity interactive controls, telemetry streams, and compliance feedback without endangering actual aircraft, the GFF AI Frontend presents a secure operational layer completely decoupled from live production model executors and database kernels.\n 13 | \n 14 | ### 1.2. Key Visual Metaphors Built Into Phase 4\n 15 | *   **The Zero-Trust Handshake**: Visual block diagrams showing AES-256 session token pathways keeping client model parameters invisible to presentation networks.\n 16 | *   **Decoupled Model Enclaves**: Isolated hypervisor-reinforced boxes representing hardware-level execution tracking protected by hardware seed security boundaries.\n 17 | *   **The Living Terminal Feed**: Live, simulated eBPF-level diagnostic event streams flowing within the login page and route-guard modal, reinforcing the premium, high-tech engineering nature of GFF AI's systems.\n 18 | *   **Role Negotiation Selector**: A highly custom bypass console allowing engineers to simulate and toggle between 7 distinct enterprise roles in real time, inspecting permission-based modules dynamically.\n 19 | \n 20 | ---\n 21 | \n 22 | ## 2. Implemented Routes & Navigation Map\n 23 | \n 24 | Phase 4 includes a fully realized, responsive, and secure routing matrix built using Next.js App Router. These public and protected paths are structured into distinct areas of operational clearance:\n 25 | \n 26 | ### 2.1. Authentication Routes (Public Preview / Entrypoints)\n 27 | *   `/login` — Central unified login terminal, defaulting to Client Portal entry.\n 28 | *   `/portal/login` — Explicit Client Portal gateway.\n 29 | *   `/admin/login` — Explicit GFF Administration gateway, defaulting to GFF Administrator credentials.\n 30 | \n 31 | ### 2.2. Client Portal Routes (`/portal/*`)\n 32 | The Client Portal is tailored for executive control, tactical project management, and cost-governance audits.\n 33 | *   `/portal/dashboard` — Unified Executive Control & Enclave Telemetry overview.\n 34 | *   `/portal/projects` — Milestone and sandbox pipeline overview.\n 35 | *   `/portal/projects/[id]` — Deep-dive tracker for an individual multi-agent project pipeline.\n 36 | *   `/portal/ai-operations` — Configurator for active agent profiles, model configurations, and memory parameters.\n 37 | *   `/portal/ai-operations/[id]` — Deep-dive sandbox editor for a specific cognitive pipeline.\n 38 | *   `/portal/control-center` — Sovereign control hub for hardware deployment and orchestrator clusters.\n 39 | *   `/portal/governance` — Live policy tracking and ISO compliance auditing.\n 40 | *   `/portal/documents` — Secure Sovereign legal vault and document index.\n 41 | *   `/portal/documents/[id]` — Inline document audit and validation engine.\n 42 | *   `/portal/billing` — Chronological \"Computational Epoch\" cost ledger and summaries.\n 43 | *   `/portal/billing/invoices` — List of current and past cryptographically signed invoices.\n 44 | *   `/portal/billing/invoices/[id]` — PDF-like interactive view of invoice ledgers.\n 45 | *   `/portal/analytics` — Dynamic resource, token, and memory lane analytics grids.\n 46 | *   `/portal/support` — SLA ticket pipeline and live wire connection.\n 47 | *   `/portal/support/[id]` — SLA wire communication log with active system engineers.\n 48 | *   `/portal/settings` — Client workspace profiles, API keys, and notification bounds.\n 49 | *   `/portal/activity` — Session tracking logs and cryptographic handshakes.\n 50 | \n 51 | ### 2.3. Admin Oversight Console Routes (`/admin/*`)\n 52 | The Admin Portal is tailored for GFF staff to manage client accounts, monitor global compute load, and handle system governance.\n 53 | *   `/admin/dashboard` — Oversight Deck with Global Telemetry, Enclave Status, and active incidents.\n 54 | *   `/admin/clients` — Master directory of all enterprise client accounts.\n 55 | *   `/admin/clients/[id]` — Dynamic client profile, active contracts, and allocated computational resources.\n 56 | *   `/admin/projects` — Global sandbox scheduler and execution milestone pipelines.\n 57 | *   `/admin/projects/[id]` — Master pipeline control room.\n 58 | *   `/admin/ai-operations` — Global model deployment, latency logs, and prompt-injection safety controls.\n 59 | *   `/admin/governance` — Master ISO compliance rules manager and guardrail template builder.\n 60 | *   `/admin/documents` — Master contract vault and blueprint compiler.\n 61 | *   `/admin/billing` — Accounts receivable ledger, contract terms manager, and computational SLA auditing.\n 62 | *   `/admin/analytics` — Global network traffic, queue latency, and multi-region cluster efficiency.\n 63 | *   `/admin/support` — Master ticket dispatcher, operator assignment, and SLA countdowns.\n 64 | *   `/admin/users` — GFF staff roster and IAM permissions management.\n 65 | *   `/admin/settings` — Global configuration, hardware regions, and emergency system boundaries.\n 66 | *   `/admin/activity` — Audit stream tracking all administrative overrides and credential rotations.\n 67 | \n 68 | ---\n 69 | \n 70 | ## 3. High-Fidelity Local Preview Auth Behavior\n 71 | \n 72 | To fulfill the \"frontend-only placeholder\" guardrails while delivering a deeply interactive premium experience, Phase 4 implements an innovative client-side authentication engine.\n 73 | \n 74 | ```\n 75 | +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 76 | |                            LOCAL PREVIEW AUTH ENGINE                              |\n 77 | |                                                                                   |\n 78 | |  1. Select Role Preset   -->   2. Auto-hydrate Mock Credentials                   |\n 79 | |  (Client Admin, etc.)          (Email, Cryptographic Salting logs)                |\n 80 | |                                                                                   |\n 81 | |  3. Trigger Handshake    -->   4. Simulate TLS Verification                       |\n 82 | |  (Password or OTP Auth)        (eBPF Terminal telemetry output animation)         |\n 83 | |                                                                                   |\n 84 | |  5. Store Session Key    -->   6. Redirect via Route Guard                        |\n 85 | |  (LocalStorage Cache)          (Enforces strict role permissions dynamically)     |\n 86 | +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 87 | ```\n 88 | \n 89 | ### 3.1. Credentials vs. One-Time Password (OTP) Dual-Mode Login\n 90 | The `/login` screen offers users a seamless mechanism to explore enterprise access models:\n 91 | 1.  **Credentials Mode**: Classic password input with built-in telemetry simulation. As the user types their password, simulated SHA-512 salting processes stream to the active console terminal.\n 92 | 2.  **MFA OTP Mode**: Simulates a rotating 6-digit One-Time Password. To mimic state-of-the-art enterprise multi-factor authentication, an automatic 30-second countdown cycle triggers the generation of new temporary tokens with simulated cryptographic rotation logs.\n 93 | \n 94 | ### 3.2. Animated Telemetry Terminal Console\n 95 | A live scrolling diagnostics feed is built directly into the login card. It streams low-noise, technical operation logs in real time, mirroring hardware-level eBPF system calls:\n 96 | *   `[INIT] Handshake request received from node terminal.`\n 97 | *   `[IDENTITY] Resolved profile context: client_admin`\n 98 | *   `[SSL/TLS] Session handshake initiated via SHA-256 cipher.`\n 99 | *   `[CRYPT] Salted passphrase vector: SHA-512_SALT_F38C...`\n100 | *   `[SANDBOX] Memory enclave isolated. Sandbox state: READY.`\n101 | \n102 | ---\n103 | \n104 | ## 4. Federated Identity & Access Management (IAM) Roles\n105 | \n106 | Phase 4 defines 7 discrete user identities across Client and Administrative boundaries, mapping directly to enterprise clearance levels.\n107 | \n108 | ### 4.1. Enterprise IAM Matrix\n109 | \n110 | | Role Key | Name | Clearance Level | Scope | Primary Responsibility |\n111 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n112 | | **`gff_admin`** | GFF Sovereign Superuser | `L-5 SYSTEM` | Global Admin & Portal | Total decentralized system override. Unfettered traversal of all client and admin enclaves. |\n113 | | **`gff_operator`** | GFF Systems Engineer | `L-4 OPERATIONAL` | Admin Console | Monitors physical infrastructure, active cluster health, queue latencies, and agent memory lanes. |\n114 | | **`finance_admin`**| GFF Financial Director | `L-3 FINANCE` | Admin & Client Billing | Oversees accounts receivable, billing tiers, epoch invoices, and SLA contract parameters. |\n115 | | **`support_agent`**| GFF Support Liaison | `L-3 SUPPORT` | Admin & Client Support | Dispatches and triage SLA tickets, maintains support channels, audits system logs. |\n116 | | **`client_admin`** | Client Administrator | `L-3 WORKSPACE` | Client Portal | Full control of client-owned sandboxes, project scopes, billing methods, and employee IAM. |\n117 | | **`client_member`**| Client Workspace Operator| `L-2 WORKSPACE` | Client Portal | Standard developer/user interface to deploy models, monitor telemetry, and view documents. |\n118 | | **`viewer`** | Global Compliance Auditor| `L-1 AUDIT` | Read-Only Views | Independent auditor node. Verifies compliance, ISO rule ledgers, and read-only activity logs. |\n119 | \n120 | ---\n121 | \n122 | ## 5. Security Route Guard Preview & Role Negotiation\n123 | \n124 | Protected paths are enclosed inside a client-side layout element (`PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`) which validates the cached session state from LocalStorage against the path's required permissions.\n125 | \n126 | ### 5.1. Dynamic Clearance Denial Overlay\n127 | When a user attempts to navigate to a section that exceeds their role's clearance level (e.g., a standard `client_member` attempting to view the Admin `/admin` suite, or a read-only `viewer` attempting to change `/portal/settings`), the route guard intercepts the render. Instead of a blank page or a raw 403 error, a premium **Clearance Violation Warning** is rendered inline:\n128 | *   **Security Alert Metrics**: Displays the user's current identity, clearance level, and the requested boundary.\n129 | *   **Interactive Counter-Sign**: Simulates a secure gateway query showing live network packets blocking traversal.\n130 | *   **Interactive Role Switcher**: A dropdown allowing users to instantly select a role with sufficient clearance, showcasing the route guard's live reactivity.\n131 | *   **Awaiting Override Countdown**: A 5-second animated gateway countdown that gracefully releases the lockout if an authorized override is simulated.\n132 | \n133 | ### 5.2. Granular Route-Access Logic\n134 | The authorization rules are codified inside `lib/preview-auth.ts`:\n135 | \n136 | ```typescript\n137 | // Client Portal clearance rules\n138 | export function canAccessPortalSection(role: PreviewRole, sectionId: string): boolean {\n139 |   if (role === \"gff_admin\") return true;\n140 |   if (role === \"viewer\") {\n141 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"analytics\", \"governance\", \"activity\"].includes(sectionId);\n142 |   }\n143 |   if (role === \"client_member\") {\n144 |     return ![\"billing\", \"settings\"].includes(sectionId);\n145 |   }\n146 |   if (role === \"client_admin\") return true;\n147 |   if (role === \"finance_admin\") {\n148 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"billing\", \"analytics\", \"activity\"].includes(sectionId);\n149 |   }\n150 |   if (role === \"support_agent\") {\n151 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"support\", \"activity\"].includes(sectionId);\n152 |   }\n153 |   if (role === \"gff_operator\") {\n154 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"projects\", \"ai-operations\", \"governance\", \"activity\"].includes(sectionId);\n155 |   }\n156 |   return false;\n157 | }\n158 | \n159 | // Admin Oversight Console clearance rules\n160 | export function canAccessAdminSection(role: PreviewRole, sectionId: string): boolean {\n161 |   if (role === \"gff_admin\") return true;\n162 |   if (role === \"gff_operator\") {\n163 |     return ![\"billing\", \"settings\", \"users\"].includes(sectionId);\n164 |   }\n165 |   if (role === \"finance_admin\") {\n166 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"clients\", \"billing\", \"analytics\", \"activity\", \"settings\"].includes(sectionId);\n167 |   }\n168 |   if (role === \"support_agent\") {\n169 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"clients\", \"support\", \"activity\", \"users\"].includes(sectionId);\n170 |   }\n171 |   if (role === \"viewer\") {\n172 |     return [\"dashboard\", \"clients\", \"projects\", \"analytics\", \"governance\", \"activity\"].includes(sectionId);\n173 |   }\n174 |   return false; // Clients cannot access Admin sections at all\n175 | }\n176 | ```\n177 | \n178 | ---\n179 | \n180 | ## 6. Detailed Module Implementations\n181 | \n182 | ### 6.1. Client Portal Module Features (`/portal/*`)\n183 | *   **Executive Control Dashboard**: Renders a comprehensive, premium grid of live eBPF-stream telemetry charts, active cluster status gauges, and hardware isolation alerts. Features real-time state monitoring and inline visual alerts.\n184 | *   **Sandbox Projects Pipeline**: Lists current active multi-agent sandbox developments. Clicking a project details card opens a narrative timeline charting progress from design to evaluation and deployment phases.\n185 | *   **Sovereign Legal & Document Vault**: A secured filing center displaying active client contracts, architecture blueprints, and service agreements. Integrates inline SHA-256 and MD5 integrity checkers for enterprise auditing.\n186 | *   **Computational Billing & Epoch Cost Ledger**: A comprehensive usage auditing suite logging resource allocation. Documents token usage, compute minutes, and network load on an epoch-by-epoch timeline with exportable audit logs.\n187 | *   **Model Configurator & Prompt Sandbox**: Allows authorized operators to toggle prompt parameters, edit short-term long-term memory lanes, and adjust security thresholds under isolated conditions.\n188 | \n189 | ### 6.2. Admin Oversight Portal Module Features (`/admin/*`)\n190 | *   **Global Oversight Deck**: Displays high-level administrative intelligence, multi-region cluster status, core processing loads, active ticketing streams, and live security events.\n191 | *   **Master Clients Directory**: A complete registry of client organizations under management. Admins can audit each client's SLA compliance matrices and allocate/revoke hardware nodes dynamically.\n192 | *   **Infrastructure Model Deployer**: Oversees regional orchestrator loads and schedules memory pruning routines.\n193 | *   **Global IAM & Users Hub**: Enables direct oversight over client employees and internal GFF staff clearance level assignments.\n194 | \n195 | ---\n196 | \n197 | ## 7. Local Mock Data Structures\n198 | \n199 | All dashboards, tables, and telemetry parameters consume structured, static mock structures modeled to mimic real-world SQL schemas and JSON payloads.\n200 | \n201 | ### 7.1. Node Cluster Database Model (`ClusterNode`)\n202 | Represents the dedicated hardware nodes allocated to running models.\n203 | ```typescript\n204 | export interface ClusterNode {\n205 |   id: string;\n206 |   nodeId: string;       // e.g., \"RETAIL-CORE-A1\"\n207 |   client: string;       // e.g., \"Sovereign Retail Group\"\n208 |   status: \"active\" | \"warning\" | \"stable\" | \"decoupled\";\n209 |   load: string;         // e.g., \"42.1%\"\n210 |   uptime: string;       // e.g., \"99.998%\"\n211 | }\n212 | ```\n213 | \n214 | ### 7.2. Invoice Ledger Model (`Invoice`)\n215 | Used to render SLA cost auditing grids.\n216 | ```typescript\n217 | export interface Invoice {\n218 |   id: string;           // e.g., \"GFF-INV-2026-004\"\n219 |   date: string;\n220 |   dueDate: string;\n221 |   amount: string;\n222 |   status: \"Settled\" | \"Overdue\" | \"Pending Handshake\";\n223 |   computationalEpochs: number;\n224 |   tokenConsumption: string;\n225 |   pdfHash: string;      // Simulated SHA-256 validation checksum\n226 | }\n227 | ```\n228 | \n229 | ### 7.3. Incident SLA Ticket Model (`SupportTicket`)\n230 | Models mission-critical operator-support pipelines.\n231 | ```typescript\n232 | export interface SupportTicket {\n233 |   id: string;           // e.g., \"SLA-9102\"\n234 |   subject: string;\n235 |   severity: \"CRITICAL (L1)\" | \"HIGH (L2)\" | \"MEDIUM (L3)\";\n236 |   status: \"Resolved\" | \"Investigating\" | \"Awaiting Handshake\";\n237 |   updatedAt: string;\n238 |   assignedOperator: string;\n239 | }\n240 | ```\n241 | \n242 | ---\n243 | \n244 | ## 8. Frontend-Only Scope & Limitations\n245 | \n246 | As configured by Phase 4 architectural guardrails, the portal and admin interfaces are **strictly client-side representations**. \n247 | \n248 | ### 8.1. State Containment\n249 | *   **Local Storage Volatility**: All state changes (modified agent prompts, newly simulated support tickets, model toggles, profile adjustments) are stored either in localized React state or synced temporarily to `localStorage`. Refreshing the browser window resets all database metrics to their baseline template configurations.\n250 | *   **Mock Verification Gateway**: No actual network connections are initiated to backend databases, server hypervisors, or identity engines. Authentication succeeds automatically on valid role-selection templates.\n251 | *   **Abstract Identity Delivery**: Email OTP inputs bypass actual verification. Clicking the \"Send OTP Code\" button triggers local terminal animations listing simulated SMTP dispatch routes, rather than delivering a real code.\n252 | \n253 | ---\n254 | \n255 | ## 9. Target Phase 5 Backend Specifications & Schema Contracts\n256 | \n257 | To transition the GFF AI sovereign operating system from frontend presentation templates to an production-ready SaaS ecosystem, the following specifications must be implemented in the future backend phase.\n258 | \n259 | ### 9.1. Future FastAPI Architecture\n260 | The target Python FastAPI application will run containerized (Docker/Kubernetes) under a secure, TLS 1.3 reverse-proxy layer. It will utilize **Pydantic v2** for robust static type verification and runtime schema enforcement.\n261 | \n262 | ```\n263 |                   +-----------------------------------+\n264 |                   |        FastAPI Gate Controller    |\n265 |                   +-----------------+-----------------+\n266 |                                     |\n267 |             +-----------------------+-----------------------+\n268 |             |                                               |\n269 |             v                                               v\n270 | +-----------------------+                       +-----------------------+\n271 | |  OAuth2 JWT Router    |                       | eBPF Telemetry Engine |\n272 | | - bcrypt/argon2 hashing|                      | - Live WebSockets     |\n273 | | - OAuth2 Bearer Tokens|                       | - Server-Sent Events  |\n274 | +-----------------------+                       +-----------------------+\n275 | ```\n276 | \n277 | ### 9.2. Recommended Database Schema (PostgreSQL / pgvector)\n278 | A multi-tenant database structure isolating client data while allowing global administrative auditing is required.\n279 | \n280 | #### `users` Table\n281 | ```sql\n282 | CREATE TABLE users (\n283 |     id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),\n284 |     email VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n285 |     password_hash VARCHAR(255) NULL, -- Null if passwordless-only\n286 |     mfa_secret VARCHAR(128) NULL,\n287 |     created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,\n288 |     updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\n289 | );\n290 | ```\n291 | \n292 | #### `roles` Table & `user_roles` Relation\n293 | ```sql\n294 | CREATE TYPE clearance_level AS ENUM ('L1', 'L2', 'L3', 'L4', 'L5');\n295 | CREATE TYPE preview_role_enum AS ENUM (\n296 |     'client_admin', 'client_member', 'gff_admin', \n297 |     'gff_operator', 'finance_admin', 'support_agent', 'viewer'\n298 | );\n299 | \n300 | CREATE TABLE roles (\n301 |     id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n302 |     name preview_role_enum UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n303 |     clearance clearance_level NOT NULL,\n304 |     description TEXT\n305 | );\n306 | \n307 | CREATE TABLE user_roles (\n308 |     user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n309 |     role_id INTEGER REFERENCES roles(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n310 |     client_id UUID NULL, -- Null for global GFF admin staff\n311 |     PRIMARY KEY (user_id, role_id)\n312 | );\n313 | ```\n314 | \n315 | #### `client_organizations` Table\n316 | ```sql\n317 | CREATE TABLE client_organizations (\n318 |     id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),\n319 |     name VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n320 |     status VARCHAR(50) DEFAULT 'active',\n321 |     contract_start TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,\n322 |     contract_end TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,\n323 |     billing_tier VARCHAR(100) DEFAULT 'premium_enterprise'\n324 | );\n325 | ```\n326 | \n327 | #### `projects` Table\n328 | ```sql\n329 | CREATE TABLE projects (\n330 |     id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),\n331 |     client_id UUID REFERENCES client_organizations(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n332 |     name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\n333 |     status VARCHAR(50) DEFAULT 'design',\n334 |     completion_percentage NUMERIC(5, 2) DEFAULT 0.00,\n335 |     created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\n336 | );\n337 | ```\n338 | \n339 | #### `telemetry_stream_logs` (TimescaleDB / Partitioned Table)\n340 | Optimized for high-throughput diagnostic event streams.\n341 | ```sql\n342 | CREATE TABLE telemetry_stream_logs (\n343 |     id BIGSERIAL,\n344 |     node_id VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n345 |     timestamp TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,\n346 |     level VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'INFO',\n347 |     module_context VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n348 |     message TEXT NOT NULL,\n349 |     sha_hash VARCHAR(64) NOT NULL -- Cryptographic integrity validation of logs\n350 | ) PARTITION BY RANGE (timestamp);\n351 | ```\n352 | \n353 | ### 9.3. Future Object Storage Specifications (AWS S3)\n354 | *   **Enveloped Encryption (AES-256-GCM)**: All corporate agreements, dynamic proposal PDFs, and blueprint maps generated by client workspaces are uploaded using server-side KMS encryption keys.\n355 | *   **Sovereign S3 Buckets**: Compliant with Singapore PDPA standards, file buckets are restricted to designated regions (e.g., `ap-southeast-1` or sovereign local private cloud endpoints).\n356 | *   **Presigned URLs**: To prevent accidental exposure of confidential legal assets, direct object access is disabled. Files are delivered exclusively via transient 5-minute presigned URLs with strict token tracking.\n357 | \n358 | ### 9.4. Real Email & OTP Dispatch Mechanics\n359 | To replace Phase 4's mock OTP behavior with a production passwordless engine:\n360 | 1.  **Transport Gateway**: Integrate **AWS SES** or **SendGrid SMTP** API.\n361 | 2.  **Transient Storage (Redis)**: Generated OTP values are cryptographically hashed and stored in Redis with a 180-second time-to-live (TTL) parameter.\n362 | 3.  **Domain Restrictors**: To enforce the GFF AI corporate posture, the backend will validate incoming signup request domains against authorized enterprise whitelists, throwing `403 Forbidden` errors for free personal providers (Gmail, Outlook, Yahoo, etc.).\n363 | \n364 | ### 9.5. Future Billing & Enterprise Payment Architecture\n365 | *   **Stripe / Chargebee Integration**: Map computational \"Epochs\" directly to automated usage-based subscription items in Stripe.\n366 | *   **Cryptographic Invoice Signatures**: Upon invoice finalization, the backend will compute a SHA-256 hash representing the ledger data, signing it with GFF AI's institutional private HSM key. The resulting hash and signature are embedded in the PDF and stored on a ledger table for client-side auditing, guaranteeing zero tampering.\n367 | \n368 | ---\n369 | \n370 | ## 10. Phase 5 Backend Build Order Recommendations\n371 | \n372 | To ensure a structured, risk-contained migration from the current high-fidelity mock architecture to a fully connected enterprise SaaS backend, the following development sprint order is highly recommended:\n373 | \n374 | ```\n375 | [SPRINT 1: Core Identity (IAM) & JWT]\n376 |        |\n377 |        v\n378 | [SPRINT 2: Multi-Tenant Database Structures]\n379 |        |\n380 |        v\n381 | [SPRINT 3: Telemetry Streams & WebSocket Endpoints]\n382 |        |\n383 |        v\n384 | [SPRINT 4: Client Sandbox Management APIs]\n385 |        |\n386 |        v\n387 | [SPRINT 5: Secure S3 File Store & SMTP OTP Integration]\n388 |        |\n389 |        v\n390 | [SPRINT 6: Enterprise Billing & SLA Ledger Audits]\n391 | ```\n392 | \n393 | ### Sprint 1: Core Identity (IAM) & JWT Authorization Middleware\n394 | *   Implement FastAPI base routing with CORS policy rules.\n395 | *   Develop user registration, secure session tokens, and role-enforcement middlewares utilizing JSON Web Tokens (JWT).\n396 | *   *Verification Matrix*: Ensure the Next.js `PreviewRouteGuard` can cleanly parse backend JWT claims to mirror the existing 7 roles exactly.\n397 | \n398 | ### Sprint 2: Multi-Tenant Postgres Schema Implementation\n399 | *   Provision a high-availability Postgres cluster.\n400 | *   Apply tables for users, clients, organizations, and project pipelines.\n401 | *   Expose standard REST CRUD endpoints for `/api/clients`, `/api/projects`, and `/api/users`.\n402 | \n403 | ### Sprint 3: Live Telemetry Streams & WebSockets\n404 | *   Set up FastAPI WebSocket router paths to serve real-time hardware telemetry and audit messages.\n405 | *   Incorporate server loops to pipe simulated server load and uptime logs into active sockets.\n406 | *   *Verification Matrix*: Replace the static timer loops in `/portal/dashboard` with direct event listeners reading from active WS sockets.\n407 | \n408 | ### Sprint 4: Sandbox Workspace & Model Enclave API controllers\n409 | *   Build control parameters for client workspaces, enabling users to edit agent configurations, save custom prompts, and toggle active LLM model engines.\n410 | *   Incorporate database persistence to store prompt variations, preventing reset on browser reloads.\n411 | \n412 | ### Sprint 5: S3 Storage & SMTP Email Gates\n413 | *   Establish AWS SDK (boto3) configurations with zero access credentials committed to source control (utilizing AWS IAM Role profiles or container environment injectors).\n414 | *   Construct SMTP email delivery handlers using secure SMTP / AWS SES.\n415 | *   Enable real passwordless verification and file downloads on `/portal/documents`.\n416 | \n417 | ### Sprint 6: billing, Stripe webhooks, and Cryptographic Signatures\n418 | *   Develop usage-tracking cron workers that aggregate computational hours.\n419 | *   Set up Stripe subscription hooks to synchronize invoice generation.\n420 | *   Build the PDF ledger builder with cryptographic signatures, satisfying corporate compliance guidelines.\n421 | \n422 | \n423 | \n424 | \n425 | ","success":true}],"durationMs":3}}
